4 I looked forward to my dinner at The Capital Grille to close out Restaurant Week in the city that never sleeps. I had dined here three times before, but not for a long while. The ambiance is all Old Vegas, the period when the Rat Pack ruled the Strip. Paintings of Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, and Sammy Davis, Jr. grace the walls, along with a young Elvis and Howard Hughes in his adult prime. Encased in glass at the northeast tip of Fashion Show, the restaurant features dark woods and has a formal feel to it. Chairs mostly fashioned of wood have fabric inserts on top and soft leather seats, while booths are all decorated in leather. From our comfortable seats we had a good view of Encore just across the street.   We opened with Pan Fried Calamari that was sauteed in Garlic Butter. Even though the chef was kind enough to accommodate my request for an aioli by producing an excellent Pepper Aioli, the calamari was the worst dish of the night. The cooking of this appetizer was very uneven. A few pieces were clearly undercooked. Some tentacles were too chewy, and were difficult to tear apart with hand or teeth and swallow. The calamari rings were much better!   A large, seemingly bottomless crock of French Onion Soup, with nicely melted Havarti Cheese, well-caramelized onions, and suitably broken down bread in the broth, was excellent. So was a cup of good and creamy New England-style Clam Chowder with a sweet clam taste as morsels of clam flattened out on the roof of the mouth and disintegrated on their way down the throat.  A chopped Caesar salad, prepared with sections of fresh Romaine Lettuce, tasty crust-like croutons, Parmesan Cheese shavings, and a delicate Caesar dressing, was also excellent.   My medium-rare Parmesan and Herb Marinated Tournedos were very good but not great. The meat seemed under-seasoned except for enough pepper. Halves of warm red and yellow Cherry and Grape Tomatoes adorned the plate. A thicker than normal au jus was substituted for unavailable requested Bordelaise Sauce. A superb Bearnaise Sauce was also provided without charge on request. But the Parmesan Cheese shavings were exactly like those that topped the Caesar Salad just a course before, which soon became too much a dose of Parmesan Cheese. Accompanying mashed potatoes and creamed spinach were delicious sides. Sam's Mashed Potatoes were Red Bliss Potatoes blended with sweet cream, butter, and salt; while the Fresh Creamed Spinach consisted of lengths of cooked spinach blended with Bechamel Sauce.   This meal was finished with an orgy of desserts!  A generous and densely packed slice of Flourless Chocolate Espresso Cake with coconut whipped cream, raspberries, and raspberry gel, plus added Vanilla Ice Cream, contained just the right amount of coffee flavoring, and was a decadent dessert. And, Classic Vanilla Creme Brulee prepared in a large dish was also excellent. Because it was the end of Restaurant Week, I also partook of some offered tasty blackberries and cool blueberries.   Service was superb all night! Not once did I have to ask for a glass of water or Iced Tea to be refilled. Our tall assistant server seemed to be always hovering nearby, quick to bring a pitcher as soon as one was even about to be needed. And, once my Iced Tea was replenished with fresh ice in a new glass. Packets of Sweet & Low were added by our always observant server Nicole. And, a whole new bread basket packed with Lavosh was brought to the table after we requested some more. Then, after meal's end, the Lavosh that we didn't eat was neatly packed for us in a box. A manager also stopped by to check on us during the course of the meal.   The Capital Grille is a classy steakhouse that we will be sure to frequent again. Other signature dishes like Butter Poached and Broiled Fresh Lobster, King Crab Legs, cheesy Au Gratin Potatoes, and a knockout Chocolate Hazelnut Cake beckon.
